## The columns

**Implementation** — the directory the image was built from, named
`<language>-<compiler>`. The unit of comparison is the tuple *(compiler, version,
flags, target ISA)*, not the language: two rows differing only in compiler are a
clean experiment, two rows differing in language are not.

**Mode** — the floating-point semantics the kernel was compiled under, which is
how much freedom the compiler was given to rewrite the arithmetic. Every mode is
`-O3`: the axis is FP semantics, never optimization on or off.

`strict` forbids FMA contraction and reassociation — for gcc, literally
`-ffp-contract=off`. `fma` allows contraction: `a*b + c` becomes a single fused
instruction that rounds **once** instead of twice, so it changes the last bit and
*increases* accuracy. It is not a sloppier mode, it is a less reproducible one.
`fast` is `-ffast-math`, which adds reassociation, and that is where precision is
genuinely sold for speed.

`strict` is not "the correct answer". It is the **reproducible** one, and it is
what makes this whole table mean anything. The kernel uses only multiply, add,
subtract and compare; IEEE 754 specifies all four to the bit, and both x86-64
(on SSE2, not the old 80-bit x87) and AArch64 conform. So once no backend is
allowed to fuse or reorder, every compiler, every language and both ISAs are
*obliged* to compute the same doubles, hence the same iteration count per pixel,
hence the same checksum. Tying every backend's hands the same way is the
precondition for comparing their timings at all: a backend that reassociated the
loop and one that did not are not running the same computation, and their run
times are not comparable.

That is why `strict` is the mode to read first, and why a row in `fma` or `fast`
is a *different experiment*, not a faster version of the same one. It is also why
some backends only ever appear in `strict`: an interpreter has one floating-point
semantics and no flags to give it another, so `fma` would be the same run under a
different name.

**Runs** — how many measured samples feed this row. Warmup rounds are recorded in
`samples.ndjson` and flagged, never deleted, but they never enter these numbers.

**Run min** — the smallest external wall-clock over those samples, measured by
the harness around `docker run`. It includes container creation, runtime
initialisation and the computation itself.

The minimum, not the mean or the median. Contention noise is **one-sided**: a
neighbour can only slow a run down, never speed it up. The fastest sample is the
one that was least disturbed, so it is the best estimate of what the machine can
actually do.

**Dispersion** — the median absolute deviation of those same samples, as a
percentage of their median.

This is a **verdict on the campaign, not an error bar on the result**. Above
roughly 2%, the machine was too noisy for percentage-level claims, and even the
minimum should be distrusted. Being a median, it is robust by design: a single
clobbered round does not show up here. Isolated spikes are found by reading
`samples.ndjson`, not by reading this column. Below three samples it reads
`n/a (n=…)`, because the lower median of `[0, d]` is `0` and a two-sample MAD
would claim a precision the campaign never had.

**Compute min** — the smallest time the program reported for its own hot loop,
measured inside the container with a monotonic clock. It excludes everything that
happened before `main`.

**Startup** — the gap between the two clocks above: container creation plus
runtime initialisation plus any JIT warmup. **This is a result, not overhead to
be subtracted.** It is where a JVM or a CPython pays its tax, and comparing it
across runtimes is one of the more interesting things this table offers.

**CPU time** — `user + system`, read from the container's own cgroup
(`/sys/fs/cgroup/cpu.stat`), median over the measured samples. It is summed across
threads, so it legitimately exceeds the wall-clock on a parallel run.

Wall-clock says whether it is fast. CPU time says at what price. A runtime whose
scheduler busy-waits burns CPU without gaining a millisecond of wall, and the gap
between these two columns is the only place you will see it. Divide it by
(run time × threads) for a parallel efficiency.

**Build min** — the smallest wall-clock of a timed recompile from a clean tmpfs,
with no network. `docker build` is preparation and is never timed; this column
comes from a `docker run` that rebuilds the source and discards the result.
`n/a` means the backend has no build step.

**Build disp.** — the same dispersion, over the build samples. Builds are slow, so
there are fewer of them, and this column reads `n/a (n=…)` more often.

**Binary** — the size of the shipped binary on disk.

**Do not rank implementations with it.** It measures linking policy, not codegen:
gcc links libc dynamically and looks tiny while the code lives in `libc.so`, Rust
links its standard library statically, Go embeds a whole runtime and its type
metadata.

**`.text`** — the size of the `.text` section: exactly the emitted code, and the
only size that is comparable across implementations. It is the **cost side of the
optimization trade**, since inlining, unrolling and vectorization all inflate it
in exchange for speed.

Calibrate your expectations on small kernels: `.text` is around a kilobyte here
and function-entry alignment padding quantises it, so a difference of a dozen
instructions can leave it completely unchanged. When it does not move, read the
disassembly. `n/a` means the backend emits no artifact — a property of the
backend, not of the language, since `native-image` produces one from the same
Java source that a JIT does not.

**Δ strict** — the run's checksum minus the strict-mode reference printed above
the table. The checksum is the sum of every pixel's iteration count, a 64-bit
integer.

On a `strict` row this column is always `0`, and that is the point rather than a
tautology. As the **Mode** entry explains, strict semantics leave the backends no
freedom to disagree, so the checksum stops being a numerical property of the
computation and becomes an **equality test between implementations** — the
correctness gate for the whole harness. A divergence aborts the campaign on the
spot, and it is never excused as a rounding difference: it means two kernels are
not computing the same thing. Something was mistyped, a condition was flipped, or
a flag leaked. Measured here: rewriting `zr2 - zi2 + cr` as `cr + zr2 - zi2` in
the Python kernel — a reassociation that reads like a harmless tidy-up — flips two
pixels out of twelve million and stops the run. This is the class of bug unit
tests do not catch.

It is a **necessary condition, not a sufficient one**. The gate only sees a
perturbation that pushes some pixel across its iteration boundary, so a passing
checksum means "no evidence of divergence at this resolution", never "provably
identical". Sensitivity grows with `--grid-size` and `--max-iter`, since both
increase the number of pixels sitting on a boundary.

The reference is not a universal constant: it is a property of *(algorithm, grid
size, iteration ceiling, viewport)*, which is why each algorithm's table carries
its own and why the value moves when you change the campaign's parameters. The
invariant is agreement between implementations, never a fixed number.

In `fma` and `fast` we do not gate — those modes are *allowed* to diverge by
construction — so the delta is reported instead: the precision sold for the speed
gained, sitting beside the timing rather than buried in a footnote. Read the two
columns together, and mind the sign of the trade: an `fma` row is typically *more*
accurate than the strict reference it differs from. The absolute checksum of a
relaxed row is not printed, because on its own it says nothing; the distance is
the whole story.

## What this report does not say

- **Which language is fastest.** It compares backends. Rows that differ in
  language are confounded by construction — different source, different runtime,
  different standard library — and are valid only for orders of magnitude.
- **How this machine compares to one of a different ISA.** Absolute cross-ISA
  timings are meaningless; only within-ISA ratios travel.
- **That a small difference is real**, unless the dispersion says it can be.
